## 6. Determination of Viability

### 6.1 Technical Feasibility

The required equipment is commercially available and well-documented. Specific acquisitions include standard FDM 3D printers, a 40W CO2 laser cutter, benchtop CNC routers, and standard electronics testing hardware. The facility requires 200-amp electrical service, industrial ventilation for fabrication areas, and compliance with the Accessible Canada Act. These requirements are standard for light industrial spaces available in Langford's McCallum Road and West Shore Parkway zones. WorkSafeBC guidelines are satisfied through a mandatory safety orientation and dual-supervisor coverage during high-risk equipment operation. **Technical feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.2 Updated Cost Analysis - 2026 Adjustment

An independent analysis of Langford, British Columbia's 2026 economic conditions necessitates an adjustment of the original March 2026 startup estimates. Inflationary pressures in the West Shore commercial real estate market and provincial wage adjustments require a recalibration of initial assumptions.

**Cost Adjustments and Identifications:**

**Underestimated Costs:** Initial personnel costs ($110,000 for 2 FTEs + Admin) were sub-market for 2026. Retaining qualified, safety-certified technical instructors in BC requires competitive compensation (estimated $65,000/year per Lead Instructor) plus a 15-20% load for mandatory benefits (WorkSafeBC premiums, CPP, EI). Furthermore, commercial lease estimates must be adjusted to $28-$30/sqft gross to accurately reflect recent municipal property tax impacts on Triple Net (NNN) leases.

**Overestimated Costs:** The initial $10,000-$20,000 marketing budget can be reduced. Organic community demand and strategic partnerships with local school districts will yield high initial conversion rates with a leaner digital marketing spend.

**Missing Cost Categories:** The original budget omitted an equipment depreciation/sinking fund and explicit accounting for commercial general liability (CGL) insurance riders specific to public-access high-risk machinery.

**Table 1: 2026 Market Cost Adjustment Matrix (Startup & Year 1)**

| Category | Initial Estimate (Lean) | 2026 Adjusted Reality (Lean) | Variance |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Facility Operations (Lease + Utilities) | $96,000 | $120,000 | +25.0% |
| Personnel (Wages + Mandatory Benefits) | $110,000 | $165,000 | +50.0% |
| Equipment, Tooling, & Shipping | $60,000 | $68,000 | +13.3% |
| Legal, Permits, & High-Risk Insurance | $20,000 | $28,000 | +40.0% |
| Marketing & Outreach | $10,000 | $6,000 | -40.0% |
| Development Labor | $17,000 | $17,000 | 0.0% |
| Equipment Sinking Fund (New) | $0 | $10,000 | N/A |
| Contingency (15% of Subtotal) | $46,950 | $62,100 | +32.2% |
| **Total Year 1 Capital Required** | **$359,950** | **$476,100** | **+32.2%** |

### 6.3 Revised Economic Feasibility

The revised 2026 cost analysis confirms that the project remains economically viable, but the break-even threshold and revenue targets must be adjusted upward.

**Table 2: Revised Annual Operating Costs (Ongoing)**

| Cost Item | Lean Model (4,000 sqft) | Expanded Model (6,000 sqft) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Facility Lease (Gross) & Utilities | $120,000 | $180,000 |
| Personnel (including Benefits) | $165,000 | $230,000 |
| Maintenance & Sinking Fund | $10,000 | $18,000 |
| Insurance, Operations & Legal | $15,000 | $22,000 |
| **Total Annual Operating** | **$310,000** | **$450,000** |

**Break-Even Discussion & Revenue Assumptions:**

Under the adjusted Lean Model, monthly operating expenses average approximately $25,833. To achieve a sustainable surplus for the contingency reserve, monthly revenue must target $29,000.

To meet this, the original membership pricing assumption must shift. The target becomes 200 active members at $60/month ($12,000), supported by $17,000 monthly distributed across workshop fees, corporate training contracts, institutional partnerships, and sustained grant funding. The commitment to capping any single funding source at 30% of total revenue remains intact, ensuring the center is shielded from abrupt grant cancellations.

**Cost Sensitivity Analysis:**

**Best-Case Scenario:** Equipment donations from institutional partners (e.g., Camosun College CTAC) offset up to $25,000 in capital expenditures; membership caps at 250 users, generating a comfortable monthly surplus.

**Expected Scenario:** Break-even is achieved in Month 8. Operating costs align with the $310,000 annual projection, requiring sustained baseline grant support alongside earned revenue.

**Worst-Case Scenario:** Commercial lease rates spike above $32/sqft or membership stalls below 120 users. The facility must immediately pivot to the Pop-Up Fallback Model to restrict overhead exposure while rebuilding community engagement.

### 6.4 Social Feasibility

Crossroads operates on a sliding-scale fee structure to ensure equitable access, mitigating the impact of the increased $60 base membership fee. Targeted outreach for low-income populations through partnerships with School Districts 61, 62, and 63 remains a priority. The volunteer mentorship cohort, projected at 15 to 25 active members, fosters a peer-support ecosystem, anchoring the facility as a vital "third place" for community development. **Social feasibility remains highly robust.**

### 6.5 Environmental and Cultural Feasibility

The project aligns cleanly with provincial initiatives promoting experiential, design-based learning. Light fabrication waste is managed via standard commercial protocols, and an emphasis is placed on iterative prototyping which inherently minimizes raw material waste. Culturally, the facility addresses the infrastructure deficit caused by rapid municipal expansion. **Environmental and cultural feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.6 Political and Legal Feasibility

Incorporation as a nonprofit society under the BC Societies Act is required to maximize public trust and grant eligibility. The updated budget properly accounts for the comprehensive Commercial General Liability and specialized riders necessary for an open-access facility housing equipment like CO2 lasers and CNC mills. Political support for workforce readiness programs in the West Shore is strong. **Political and legal feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.7 Operational Feasibility

The operational model relies on two full-time safety instructors working staggered shifts to cover 63 staffed hours per week, with an overlapping presence during peak afternoon and weekend hours. A mandatory safety orientation protocol complies with provincial health and safety mandates. **Operational feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.8 Schedule Feasibility

A 12-month phased implementation timeline is maintained:

- **Months 1 to 3:** Nonprofit incorporation and lease negotiation.
- **Months 4 to 6:** Facility renovation and equipment commissioning.
- **Months 7 to 9:** Soft launch, pilot workshops, and protocol testing.
- **Months 10 to 12:** Full public launch and comprehensive evaluation.

**Schedule feasibility is confirmed.**

---

## 7. Conclusion and Recommendation

This feasibility study confirms that the Crossroads Community STEM Centre remains viable in the 2026 economic landscape. While regional market pressures in Langford, specifically commercial real estate rates and professional wage benchmarks, have increased the Year 1 Lean Model startup requirement to $476,100, the underlying demand for accessible technical education is thoroughly validated.

**Recommendation:** The project should immediately proceed to the funding acquisition phase utilizing the adjusted Lean Model (Alternative A). The revised operational budget of $310,000 annually is sustainable given the calculated break-even threshold of 200 members and diversified ancillary revenue streams. Execution should commence with the formalization of the nonprofit society and the initiation of targeted grant applications to secure the necessary startup capital.

